<span class=title> Re: uhm...</span><hr size=1> Hmm... I'm not a lawyer, but it seems like it would fall under &quot;unlawful search &amp; siezure&quot; as far as the Fourth Amendment is concerned (for those of us in the US). However, I'm fairly sure this applies only to the government's activities, and am not really sure if there's a parallel law restricting private citizens and corporations in the same way.<br>
<br>
Now that I think of it, there may not be... I'm thinking about private investigators and the fact that they don't need probable cause or anything to follow people around, take pictures, etc.<br>
<br>
However it seems like it may be unethical and would get all sorts of privacy groups pissed off at Sony/SOE if they did something like this. Bad PR move at the very least. <p>--<br>
