<br>
While a State authority must have probable cause to search and seize anything they find, the private citizen is not really under such stricture.  Meaning that a corporation, as a public entity, is considered a &quot;citizen&quot;.  Now, if a private citizen walks into someone's home and notices a bloody knife on the kitchen counter, and they have heard of a murder where a knife was involved, the citizen can take the knife and turn it over to the police, without having impeded on his neighbor's civil rights.  It could be said that he &quot;stole&quot; the knife, but that is something the neighbor would have to press charges on and frankly, not worth the Class A misdemeanor it might be.<br>
<br>
Extrapolate a moment here though.  If it is illegal for me to enter your connection to the internet via my computer and scan your computer for processes, files, etc., without your permission, it is also illegal for Sony to do the same, the EULA notwithstanding as we all know that if it was challenged in court it would be thrown out within 5 moments.<br>
<br>
Now, there are some processes in Windoze that necessitate, via the permissions we tab on our internet options, constant updating by servers associated with which ever programs we have running that need to be connected to an outside computer to run efficiently, a la a virus scanner or weather checker.  Everquest is not one of these programs.  I can also tell you this, the GMs and Guides cannot scan your computer.  The most the GMs can do is capture your IP and traceroute it via your log in.  They cannot, themselves, enter your computer and have it spit our which processes are running and why and where and how.  If they did this, and we would have to agree that this is without your informed consent, they would be breaking the law that all computer users are bound to.  Whether they act as a private person or public entity, they cannot scan your computer in any way, shape or form without your informed consent.<br>
<br>
This does not include the packets that are sent to and from your computer and their servers which are necessary for playing the game.  It is not necessary for the game to know what's going on in your computer to run.  Now, Windoze needs to know what's going on within your computer for it to run properly, but those scans are all internal and solely based on the computer that operationg system is loaded on.  In other words, it will scan your computer alone, not all the compters on a network. With that said, we can safely say that, as a going concern, Windoze OS does not break that part of the law.<br>
<br>
What about the IE Updates? You say.  You can turn the update scanning on or off in your Options Screen.  If you say yes, scan my computer (and in this case they only scan the IE folder) for needed updates, then you are giving informed consent for their servers to scan your computer and even limit it to a narrow perimeter.  This goes for any automatic updating you have for any program you have loaded on your computer.  These updates will only scan on one particular computer, and not any other machines on a network that may also have the program running. You would have to make sure each computer is authorized for scans.<br>
<br>
So, since we are all talking about 3rd Partyware in general and ShowEQ in particular, you can safely say that if you did authorize Sony to scan you computer, it still would not pick up Show EQ since that program is run on a Linux server connected via network and you are only giving them permission to scan your computer with EQ on it, not your entire network.  It would be safe to say that if they did the scan then banned you for using ShowEQ you could take them to court for illegal scanning of your network since that would be the only way they could find it.  If you're worried about 3rd Partyware, you can narrow the perimiters and tell them that they are only allowed to scan your EQ folder... if they saw anything outside that scope it would be inadmissable as you only gave permission for them to scan one directory and the folders thereunder.<br>
<br>
I think that I am correct in this, however, I will admit that I could be wrong.  I would have to go look up case law.  Let me know if you would like any citations and I will try to get them for you. <p><img src=http://24.26.194.142/sevepic.gif></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lannlaarcrimsonlite>Lannlaar Crimsonlite</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 51<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/12/03 2:37:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25937.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: uhm...</span><hr size=1> Seve and Moto hit it dead on <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=33046" target="top"><br>
